    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1684574808" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1684574808" />
    <a title="Jan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57282794-jan"><img alt="Jan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1505016022p2/57282794.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1684574808?book_show_action=true">Jul 01, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jan" href="/user/show/57282794-jan">Jan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57282794-jan?shelf=twentieth-century">twentieth-century</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57282794-jan?shelf=actors">actors</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1684574808" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5153810871530742482">On this my second reading (after several years) I was pleasantly surprised by this book. This time, I really liked it, whereas on my first read I think I was a bit lukewarm. <br/><br/>I have recently been reading about the bad behaviour of some of the twentieth century&apos;s Hollywood stars, including Errol Flynn. Much loved in the movies, but IRL apparently he was pretty much addicted to alcohol and sex. Then I had a vague memory of reading a book once before, about a (fictional) illegitimate daughter of Err</span>
  <span id="freeText5153810871530742482" style="display:none">On this my second reading (after several years) I was pleasantly surprised by this book. This time, I really liked it, whereas on my first read I think I was a bit lukewarm. <br /><br />I have recently been reading about the bad behaviour of some of the twentieth century's Hollywood stars, including Errol Flynn. Much loved in the movies, but IRL apparently he was pretty much addicted to alcohol and sex. Then I had a vague memory of reading a book once before, about a (fictional) illegitimate daughter of Errol Flynn. I tracked it down to Glitter Baby, and thought I'd give it another try. And this time, the sections with Errol Flynn rang so true. I found it very plausible that he could have had a daughter like Fleur, and I got hooked in her dramatic story. <br /><br />Fleur, through no fault of her own, is brought up in terrible circumstances. Her father Errol Flynn died when she was very young, never knowing of her existence. Fleur also has no idea that he was her real father.<br /><br />Fleur is surrounded by horrible people who use her for their own ends. Her own mother Belinda is shallow, selfish and helpless. Trapped in an unhappy life of her own making, Belinda lives vicariously through Fleur, forcing Fleur into a life she doesn't want but is too young and naive to be able to escape from.<br /><br />Fleur's rich European stepfather is twisted and truly horrible and creepy. He uses and manipulates people, and seeks revenge when his own warped desires are thwarted. <br /><br />Fleur has been blessed with a fair amount of her (biological) father's natural appeal and charisma. But as a young woman, her life is bound up and manipulated by her twisted mother and stepfather. She becomes a successful model, and also begins a career in movies. But it's not what Fleur would choose for herself. When she meets and falls for hot young writer and actor Jake, their relationship becomes tainted by her mother's interference. <br /><br />It takes years for Fleur to eventually find herself and what she really wants. I liked her character, and the twists and turns of her story kept me interested all the way through. I also liked Jake, although it was much later in the book when we really learned much about him and what drives him. This book is basically Fleur's story.<br /><br />This time through I found the storyline quite plausible, even though the behaviour of some characters is extreme. After reading about the real life behaviour of some of the old 'matinee idols', and also about some of the horrible stage mothers who were quite happy to pimp out their daughters just to get them into movies, it wasn't hard to believe in characters like Belinda and Alexi.<br /><br />So for me, this time around this turned out to be a fast-moving and involving story, and one of Ms Phillips' better books. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="5153810871530742482" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

