<div id="review_123307532" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/123307532" />
    <a title="Jim son of Jim (formerly PhotoJim)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2640658-jim-son-of-jim-formerly-photojim"><img alt="Jim son of Jim (formerly PhotoJim)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1265458413p2/2640658.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/123307532?book_show_action=true">Sep 24, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jim son of Jim (formerly PhotoJim)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jim son of Jim (formerly PhotoJim)" href="/user/show/2640658-jim-son-of-jim-formerly-photojim">Jim son of Jim (formerly PhotoJim)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2640658-jim-son-of-jim-formerly-photojim?shelf=2010-reads">2010-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2640658-jim-son-of-jim-formerly-photojim?shelf=romance">romance</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer123307532" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7707839427500465712">First let me say that I&apos;m a big SEP fan. I almost always enjoy her characters. She has creative plot lines and snappy dialog. So what would one of her earlier books be like? Let&apos;s travel all the way back to 1987, when hair was big and portable phones required a five pound battery. Although that was the original publish date, it wasn&apos;t the date of the book setting.<br/><br/>Our story begins when a stupid obnoxious twit changes her name to Belinda and runs away to Hollywood to fall in love with the stars. B</span>
  <span id="freeText7707839427500465712" style="display:none">First let me say that I'm a big SEP fan. I almost always enjoy her characters. She has creative plot lines and snappy dialog. So what would one of her earlier books be like? Let's travel all the way back to 1987, when hair was big and portable phones required a five pound battery. Although that was the original publish date, it wasn't the date of the book setting.<br /><br />Our story begins when a stupid obnoxious twit changes her name to Belinda and runs away to Hollywood to fall in love with the stars. Belinda shows herself throughout the book to be petty, weak minded, vindictive, uncaring, untalented, manipulative, and a total slut to boot. Let's just say that Belinda will not be making any parent of the year lists. Ever. And as bad as Belinda, our heroine's mother is, her 'father' is much worse.<br /><br />An inordinate amount of time is spent on the past and in backstory. While this may annoy some, I like the way that it sets the stage and gives most of the character's motivations. When Fleur Savager, our actual heroine, does something, we can all look at her past and know where she's coming from. And boy does she have places to come from. <br /><br />I thought the story took awhile to get anywhere. I thought it was dated. I thought a couple of the characters were a little too evil to be believed. I didn't believe a couple of plot devices. And yet I really enjoyed this book. More complicated than the usual romance novel. Better written too.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7707839427500465712" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


