    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_58867926" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/58867926" />
    <a title="Charity" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/458849-charity"><img alt="Charity" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1514593007p2/458849.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/58867926?book_show_action=true">Jun 08, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Charity" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Charity" href="/user/show/458849-charity">Charity</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780061438561" href="/book/show/3529837-glitter-baby">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/458849-charity?shelf=romance">romance</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/458849-charity?shelf=owned">owned</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer58867926" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3220380320274260770">I confess: this is my first look at Susan Elizabeth Phillips&apos; work. I understand that she&apos;s one of the best in the genre, and I&apos;ve heard plenty about GLITTER BABY, this reprint of what might amount to early women&apos;s fiction. Mega-author Sandra Brown&apos;s quote on the cover stating that the work was &quot;A highly entertaining story. GLITTER BABY is a must for readers of women&apos;s fiction&quot; is what actually convinced me to snatch this book from the &quot;freebie&quot; pile at my chapter&apos;s RWA meeting. I am SO GLAD I d</span>
  <span id="freeText3220380320274260770" style="display:none">I confess: this is my first look at Susan Elizabeth Phillips' work. I understand that she's one of the best in the genre, and I've heard plenty about GLITTER BABY, this reprint of what might amount to early women's fiction. Mega-author Sandra Brown's quote on the cover stating that the work was "A highly entertaining story. GLITTER BABY is a must for readers of women's fiction" is what actually convinced me to snatch this book from the "freebie" pile at my chapter's RWA meeting. I am SO GLAD I did.<br /><br />To start, I really wasn't sure how the book was going to lay out. I felt that it got off to a slow start, opening with the Glitter Baby's return to society and whetting my appetite for what would happen next. I didn't understand, early on, how integral the backstory would be, and so I read on cautiously since I had never been a fan of a lot of backstory. But when I read the last page, I couldn't help but feel grateful for the trip down the character's history lane. It gave the book a much bigger, more colossal completeness that I was awed by Phillips' skill and story-wearving.<br /><br />If you read women's fiction and romance, pick up this novel. You fall in love with Phillips' characters and despise her villians throughout this novel. A growing sense of intensity grips you as the delicate balance of relationships Fleur has with her family reaches it's apex, and you nearly heave a sigh of relief when that conflict is resolved. The love story in this novel, for some reason, appears secondary to Fleur's growth into an ambitious, self-made woman. In romance, this can be tricky, but for this novel (working as "women's fiction"), it works beautifully as the story is centered on Fleur's journey, beginning to end.<br /><br />A fantastic story that grew more spell-binding by the page. I'm grateful I have anothe SEP novel in my cue to read, for I now know whose work I'll be picking up more often in the bookstore!</span>
  <a data-text-id="3220380320274260770" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


